On June 19, Felipe was formally proclaimed 
monarch and swore an oath at a ceremony with lawmakers in Parliament. It was a no-frills event, though the 18th-century 
Spanish crown and 17th-century scepter were on display.

After
 a brief military parade, King Felipe VI and Queen Letizia took a
drive through some of Madrid's most emblematic 
streets and monuments - such as the Prado Museum and the Cibeles 
fountain.

The palace 
acknowledged that the customary pomp had been eliminated 'in keeping 
with the criteria of austerity that the times recommend.'

